Image Segementation¶

Image segementation is a technique of partitioning an image into multiple segements. The process is useful to indentify objects with relevant information.

In [6]:
import numpy as np
import cv2
import skimage
from skimage import io
from skimage import external

% matplotlib inline
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

The Image¶

In [7]:
fig, (ax1, ax2)= plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(20,16))
import matplotlib.patches as patches

# Image
img_gray = cv2.imread('high_res_img.tif',0)

ax1.imshow(img_gray,cmap='gray')
ax1.set_title('Original Image')
ax1.add_patch(patches.Rectangle((1750,3750),
                                  250, 250,
                                  fill=False,
                                  edgecolor="Red"))
#Subset_area
img_a= img_gray[3750:4000, 1750:2000]
ax2.imshow(img_a,cmap='gray')
ax2.set_title('Subset Image')
plt.show()

Denoising the image¶

Deonising an image is a technique of smoothening interior of grains, while keeping sharp edges between grains.

In [8]:
plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(20,16))
from skimage import restoration
from skimage import img_as_float
img_float = img_as_float(img_a)
img_denoised= restoration.denoise_nl_means(img_float, h=0.001, multichannel=False)

plt.subplot(121),plt.imshow(img_a,cmap='Blues'),plt.xticks([]), plt.yticks([])
plt.title('Orignal')
plt.subplot(122),plt.imshow(img_denoised,cmap='Blues'), plt.xticks([]),plt.yticks([])
plt.title('Denoised')
plt.show()

Edge detection using Canny¶

In [13]:
plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(20,16))

# Orignal
from skimage import feature
edges_o = feature.canny(img_a, sigma=0.1,
                        low_threshold=0.001,
                        high_threshold=0.009)

plt.subplot(121), plt.imshow(img_denoised, cmap='nipy_spectral'),
plt.contour(edges_o), plt.title('Original')

# Denoised
edges_d = feature.canny(img_denoised, sigma=0.1,
                        low_threshold=0.001,
                        high_threshold=0.009)
plt.subplot(122), plt.imshow(img_denoised, cmap='nipy_spectral')
plt.contour(edges_d), plt.title('Denoised')
plt.show()

Top-Hat Transform¶

Top-hat transform is an operation that extracts small elements and details from given images.

In [14]:
plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(20,16))

from scipy import ndimage
from skimage import morphology

wat_img_a= ndimage.black_tophat(img_float, 10)
wat_img_a -= 0.3* img_float
wat_img_a= morphology.dilation(wat_img_a)
plt.subplot(121),plt.imshow(wat_img_a, cmap='nipy_spectral')
plt.title('Original')

wat_img= ndimage.black_tophat(img_denoised, 10)
wat_img -= 0.3* img_denoised
wat_img= morphology.dilation(wat_img)
plt.subplot(122),plt.imshow(wat_img, cmap='nipy_spectral')
plt.title('Denoised')

plt.show()

Watershed Segementation¶

In [38]:
plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(20,16))
from skimage import morphology

x, y = np.load('clicks.npy').T
plt.subplot(121), plt.imshow(img_denoised, cmap='gray')
plt.plot(y,x, 'or', ms=4)


from skimage import morphology
markers = np.zeros(img_denoised.shape, dtype=np.int)
markers[x.astype(np.int), y.astype(np.int)] = np.arange(len(x)) + 1
markers = morphology.dilation(markers, morphology.disk(7))



# markers = np.zeros(img_denoised.shape, dtype=np.int)
# markers[x.astype(np.int), y.astype(np.int)] = np.arange(len(x)) + 1
# markers = morphology.dilation(markers, morphology.disk(7))

labels_hat = morphology.watershed(wat_img, markers)
# from skimage import color
color_labels = color.label2rgb(labels_hat, img_denoised)
plt.subplot(122), plt.imshow(color_labels)

plt.show()

Laplace filter¶

In [53]:
# A different markers image: laplace filter
plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(20,7))

plt.subplot(121), plt.imshow(img_denoised, cmap='gray')

lap = ndimage.gaussian_laplace(img_denoised, sigma=0.005)
lap = restoration.denoise_nl_means(lap, h=0.0002, multichannel=False)
plt.subplot(122), plt.imshow(lap, cmap='Spectral'); plt.colorbar()
plt.show()
